<HL> Sun Microsystems Slashes Price 36%
On Workstation to Thwart IBM, Apple
---
By Brenton R. Schlender
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> SUNW XLGX
COMPUTERS (EDP) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. slashed the price of its least expensive computer workstations 36% in an attempt to preempt encroachment into its markets by powerful new personal computers from Apple Computer Inc. and International Business Machines Corp. 

   "We've basically declared war on the low-end workstation market," said Scott McNealy, Sun's president and chief executive officer, who contends that the new prices for Sun's 3/50M workstations make them less costly than comparably equipped personal computers. 
The 3/50M, now priced at $4,995, is used by professional printers for typesetting and page layout, and by engineers designing everything from computer software to automobiles and jet engines. 

   Mountain View, Calif.-based Sun announced the price cuts within a month of announcements by both IBM and Apple of their intent to enter the market for technical workstations with souped up personal computers. 

   Last week, for example, IBM announced a series of new personal computers, including its Personal System/2 Model 80, which is built around an Intel Corp. 80386 microprocessor. 
The machine, priced from $6,995, will be capable of many of the sophisticated engineering tasks that Sun's workstations can perform, but software for those functions won't be available until late next year. 
In March, Apple unveiled its Macintosh II, priced from $4,800 and aimed squarely at the engineering, publishing and technical workstation markets. 

   Both the IBM and Apple machines, however, require the purchase of software and accessories to match the performance of the Sun workstation. 

   "The difference between us and them is that they're announcing products that will become available in the next 12 to 18 months, while we're shipping ours in volume," said Mr. McNealy in an interview. 
"Plus, we have over 850 software applications that will work right now, not next year," he added. 

   Historically, markets for technical workstations have been rather small. 
Analysts estimate that since its founding in 1981, Sun has sold about 38,000 workstations, most of which are 3/50M models. 
Its main competitor, Chelmsford, Mass.-based Apollo Computer Inc., has sold about 30,000 workstations, and analysts estimate that other manufacturers such as Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co. have sold about 35,000 workstations. 
By contrast, about nine million personal computers have been sold. 

   But as the distinction begins to blur between personal computers and more sophisticated workstations, both in terms of price and performance, market opportunities broaden for both industries. 
Indeed, Mr. McNealy said he would like to see Sun expand its markets down into areas traditionally served by personal computer manufacturers -- such as more conventional office automation -- even as personal computer makers are attempting to move into more sophisticated markets. 

   "We think there's the opportunity to sell in the tens of thousands of workstations easily, if not more than that" each year, Mr. McNealy said. 
"Our factory is primed so we can pump these out like cookies." 

   Analysts say Sun's aim is defensive as much as anything. 
"Sun is certainly mindful of competition from three areas: IBM, Apple and folks in the Far East like NEC Corp.," said Robert Herwick, an analyst for Hambrecht &amp; Quist, a San Francisco-based investment banking firm. 
"They have to be looking over their shoulder all the time," Mr. Herwick added. 

   That's because Sun's workstations run software that uses an industry standard operating system called Unix. 
While that means the Sun machines have access to a greater library of software, it also leaves their hardware vulnerable to being cloned, much like IBM's personal computers, especially as manufacturing costs decline. 

   In response to Sun's announcement, Cupertino, Calif.-based Apple's manager of business marketing, John Zeisler, said he didn't think Sun's pricing strategy would necessarily pit the two companies against each other. 
"Sun workstations typically are sold in a configuration of five or eight workstations, while a Macintosh II will be more of a stand-alone workstation," he said. 

   A spokesman for Apollo Computer said that the company doesn't have any workstations directly competing with the low end of Sun's line, and that its units remain priced competitively against Sun's more powerful models. 
He said Apollo doesn't have any plans for price cuts at the current time. 
Armonk, N.Y.-based IBM said it doesn't comment on announcements by competitors. 

   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Sun shares fell $2.375 to close at $32. 

   Separately, Burlington, Mass.-based Xylogics Inc. said it received a $20 million contract to supply disk controllers to Sun for two years. 

</TEXT>
