<TEXT>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. said it raised prices on its workstations by an average of 7%, passing on to customers the higher cost for computer components such as DRAM memory chips. 

   Sun's move follows the trend of recent price increases by such companies as Digital Equipment, IBM and Apple Computer. 

   The increase, for example, raises the price of Sun's entry level workstation, the Sun-3/50, to $5495 from $4995. 
Also raised 7% were prices for Sun's file server products. 
System prices for newer products were raised an average of 6%, while prices for older product lines were hiked by 10% to 15%. 

   Sun, based in Mountain View, Calif., said the increased prices will help the company purchase larger quantities of memory components, thereby increasing manufacturing and driving down "unacceptably long lead times" for its products. 

