<LP>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Hewlett-Packard Co. said it will
unveil today a low-priced workstation aimed at business
users, the latest in a recent volley of inexpensive yet
powerful new workstations from makers who are battling for
new markets.
   The new machine, the Model 425e, will rival in price the
lowest-priced workstations on the market. The 425e will list
for $5,490 but runs as much as 76% faster, for example, than
Sun Microsystems Inc.'s bottom-end machine, the $4,995
Sparcstation SLC, Hewlett-Packard said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard, Sun and other workstation makers are
trying to expand the market for their workstations into the
office -- usually the turf of personal computers and
mainframes. "That's the real sweet spot of the market," said
Karl Freund, Hewlett-Packard's workstation-marketing manager.
   Mr. Freund said Hewlett-Packard engineers tailored the
425e to the business user by stripping out features such as
fast graphics and special printer sockets that, while vital
to workstations' usual engineering users, aren't needed for
most business tasks but add cost to a machine.
   The new Hewlett-Packard machine, on the other hand,
includes amenities that makers have until now kept out of
their low-priced workstations to hold down to around $5,000.
Sun's bare-bones SLC and Hewlett-Packard's older $4,990 400DL
workstation are monochrome-only machines that are limited to
16 megabytes of internal memory and can't accept internal
hard-disk drives.
   Hewlett-Packard said its new 425e, which uses Motorola
Inc.'s 68040 microprocessor chip, can plug into color
monitors, can contain as many as 48 megabytes of internal
memory and can hold as much as an 840 megabyte hard-disk
drive. The machine has circuitry to process audio
information, such as music from compact disks or speech from
a microphone, and store it in digital form on hard-disk
drives.
   Hewlett-Packard said it has received orders for 10,000 of
the new machines, including an order valued at $40 million
from GTE Corp.'s GTE Telephone Operations unit.
Hewlett-Packard said it also will announce today two new
higher-end 425 models -- the Model 425t for $8,990 and the
425s for $21,490 -- which will include additional features
such as more memory.
