<HL>
   Who's News:
   Sun Microsystems Inc.
   Is Planning to Form
   2 Wholly Owned Units
</HL>
<DATE>
02/14/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS SUNW
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- Sun Microsystems Inc. said it
will form two companies to develop and market certain
software and hardware products.
   Sun, a maker of computer workstations, said it will
operate the companies as wholly owned subsidiaries. One new
subsidiary, SunSoft Inc., will develop and market Unix
operating software and user interfaces written for Sun's
Sparc computer architecture. Edward J. Zander, formerly vice
president of marketing at Sun, was named president of
SunSoft.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The other new subsidiary, SunTech Enterprises Inc., will
manage so-called value-added products, such as Sun's printers
and software used to connect Sun machines to other computers.
Eric E. Schmidt, previously vice president of Sun's general
systems group, will be the unit's president.
   The new companies will be fully operational July 1, Sun
said.
   Sun President Scott G. McNealy said that splitting off the
businesses will help the company focus its various products
better in specific markets. Until now, he said, "we have had
too many products going out through one monolithic $3 billion
sales organization."
   The move is also meant to allay criticism in the industry
that Sun, by selling both machines and the software needed to
run them, has an unfair advantage against other computer
makers that hope to use Sun's Sparc architecture in "clone"
machines. But now, because the two new companies will be
responsible for their own profits and losses, analysts say
they wouldn't be inclined to give Sun early access to new
technologies. So, "clone manufacturers have a level playing
field," Mr. McNealy said.
</TEXT>
