SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Microsoft Corp. are piecing
together an industry coalition to attack the fast-growing
workstation market now led by Sun Microsystems Inc.
   The group hopes to bring together at least five computer
companies, including Digital Equipment Corp., to create a new
standard design for workstations, said people familiar with
the discussions. Today's workstations -- more powerful than
personal computers and often used by scientists and engineers
-- lack the kind of de facto software standard that has made
personal computers so successful.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If it succeeds, the coalition could rob market share from
Sun and from companies such as Intel Corp. and Motorola Inc.,
which make the microprocessor chips that operate most of
today's desktop computers. But it will surely face powerful
opposition from Intel and Motorola, each of which plans to
unveil new super-chips this year and next.
   Because of the expected slowdown in personal computer
sales in 1991, Compaq and other personal computer makers have
been searching for a hot technology to lure buyers. And
workstations are expected to grow at a continued faster pace.
The industry group has already sketched out a preliminary
blueprint for their workstation, sources say, but isn't
expected to announce its plans for at least a month and won't
market the workstations for more than a year.
   If the group proceeds, Santa Cruz Operations Inc. would
develop crucial operating-system software and Microsoft would
provide a version of its popular Windows operating software.
The electronic brains of the workstation will be a powerful
microprocessor using reduced-instruction-set-computing. This
RISC technology allows chips to operate faster by reducing
their complexity. The favored candidate is the R4000 chip
announced earlier this month by its designer, Mips Computer
Systems Inc., industry experts say.
   A decision to standardize on the R4000 chip would be a
bonanza for Mips, of Sunnyvale, Calif. But the company's
president, Robert Miller, reached by phone Saturday,
cautioned that talk of Compaq and others agreeing to
standardize on the chip "is still speculative."
   Such a workstation alliance would be a blow to Sun, which
quickly became the biggest maker of workstations in the late
1980s, but now could be forced to compete with several strong
companies backing a single alternative design. People
familiar with the group's discussions said the Sun-designed
Sparc chip, which also employs RISC, has been ruled out
despite heavy pressure from Sun on Compaq to use the chip.
   Any coalition must contend with Intel's technological and
marketing might. By the time the industry alliance produces
its first machine, Intel will have announced its new 80586
chip and shipped faster versions of its 80486 chip. Both
Intel chips will adhere to existing industry standards.
   In 1988, Compaq and other companies banded together to
develop a PC standard known as Extended Industry Standard
Architecture. The so-called "Gang of Nine" successfully
developed and built EISA PCs to compete with the standard set
by International Business Machines Corp. known as the Micro
Channel Architecture.
   Compaq, Microsoft and Mips officials refused to comment on
the existence of the group.
   ---
   G. Pascal Zachary contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
