<HL> Compaq to Introduce Speedier Versions
Of Portables, Desktops Using 80386 Chip
---
By Paul Duke Jr.
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 09/24/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CPQ
COMPUTERS (EDP)
ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp. is expected to introduce next week speedier versions of its top-of-the-line portable and desktop computers. 

   The moves are Compaq's first product introductions since International Business Machines Corp. revamped its personal computer line in April and indicate that Compaq is following its tested strategy of trying to leapfrog IBM performance and concentrate on high-powered business computers. 

   At the same time, Compaq apparently hasn't moved to copy some of the deviations from the standard-setting 1981 IBM design that the computer giant made in April, a sign that the Houston-based company believes there is still a big and lucrative market for computers based on the earlier design. 
Compaq personal computers -- as well as those from other big makers like Tandy Corp., American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., or Leading Edge Products Inc., for instance -- are built around the six-year-old IBM-PC design. 

   Industry sources expect Compaq to introduce an update of its Deskpro 386 computer using a faster version of the Intel Corp. 80386 microprocessor, known as a 386 chip, that powers the current Deskpro 386 models. 
The new version, also made by Intel, will operate 25% faster than previous 386 chips, which will speed up software programs run on the computer. 

   The microprocessor is the "brain" of the computer, which electronically performs the computer's operations. 
The Intel 386 chip is currently the most powerful microprocessor available for IBM-compatible computers. 

   Compaq officials wouldn't discuss the new products, which are expected to be introduced at a news conference the company has scheduled for next Tuesday in New York. 

   IBM announced in April a computer scheduled to be available in the fourth quarter with a 386 chip running at the same speed as Compaq's expected models. 
It isn't clear when Compaq's computers would reach stores, but Compaq models generally have hit the market within a few weeks after introduction. 
Sources familiar with the expected Compaq announcement weren't sure of the prices for the new models. 
Compaq's current Deskpro 386 models start at about $7,000 including a monitor; the price of the new machine is likely to be slighly higher. 

   The move to the faster chips is yet another step in the growth of personal computer power, as small desktop units increasingly take over tasks that only a few years ago required larger, free-standing minicomputers. 
The faster chip will make personal computers more attractive for use in architecture, design, or industrial management applications that use big, complicated software programs that bog down on less-powerful microcomputers. 

   That market has been served by workstation makers like Apollo Computer Inc. and Sun Microsystems Inc. 
A workstation is a powerful personal computer for engineers and other professionals that is faster and has better graphics and communications links than office desktop computers. 

   One industry source, who asked not to be identified, said Compaq would offer as an option on the new models a graphics device that incorporates some workstation technology. 

   "It'll give (the Compaq entries) the amazing graphics that have so far been available only on workstations. 
And it should be better even than the improved graphics on the new IBM line," the source said. 

   Tim Bajarin, vice president of the Creative Strategies market research firm in Santa Clara, Calif., said, "Compaq's move will create a big collision with the workstation market. 
It's the first time you'll have a (personal computer) with workstation power." 

   While Compaq is improving its graphics to match advances made by IBM in its April line, sources said the Compaq models won't mimic the most important change in the new IBM computer -- the "microchannel," IBM's term for the pathway between the parts of the computer that actually perform computations and other parts like the memory, storage, modems and printers. 
The microchannel has caused some controversy in the computer industry because it smoothes out the pathway used in previous models, but at the cost of making obsolete some peripheral devices, such as modems, which worked with computers based on the 1981 design. 

   Compaq had said earlier this year it planned to introduce at least one computer that didn't copy the new pathway. 
In doing so next week, Compaq will be directly challenging IBM's new line in the big business market. 
That is a sign of Compaq's belief that buyers still aren't completely enamored of the new IBM line, and also, perhaps, that the new IBM computers are proving more difficult to copy both technically and legally than the old line. 

   Compaq is also expected to announce a version of its popular Portable III model with the 386 chip, a machine that has been expected for months. 
Compaq was the first major manufacturer to introduce a personal computer using the 386 last year, but it won't be the first to introduce a portable with the chip. 
Toshiba Corp. of Japan a few weeks ago introduced in Europe the first portable to use the 386 chip; the model isn't yet available in the U.S. IBM doesn't offer a portable with the 386 chip. 

</TEXT>
