<HEAD>Sun Unveils New Workstations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. on Monday introduced
four new workstations that it called faster and more sophisticated
machines which form the high end of the company's desktop line.
   The new SPARCstation 2 computers are almost twice as fast as the
SPARCstation 1 models introduced last year, Sun said. They range
from a $14,995 monochrome-display workstation to a $49,985
color-screen version offering three-dimensional modeling and
animation.
   Workstations are high-powered personal computers aimed primarily
at scientists, engineers and others who need great computing
capacity or high-quality graphics.
   ``The addition of the SPARCstation 2 line with its great
graphics simply makes this environment better for technical
professionals who have real performance needs,'' said Scott
McNealy, president and chief executive officer of the Mountain
View-based company.
   Like its predecessor, the SPARCstation 2 uses the popular Unix
operating system and Open Look graphical interface and packages the
electronics in a small ``pizza box'' enclosure. But while the
earlier models offered from 8 to 48 megabytes of memory, the new
ones offer 16 to 96 megabytes. A megabyte is roughly a million
characters of information.
   The new line also includes a low-cost file server, a computer
that acts as the hub of a network of desktop machines.
   The new products are being offered in addition to the $4,995
SPARCstation SLC and $7,995 IPC desktops introduced last year.
