<HL> Digital Equipment Corp. Slashes Prices
On Workstations in Bid to Gain in Market
---
By William M. Bulkeley
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 06/17/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> DEC
COMPUTERS (EDP) </IN>
<DATELINE> MAYNARD, Mass.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. slashed prices on its computer workstations in an effort to gain ground in a fast-growing market where its results have been weak. 

   The price cuts surprised analysts and competitors, and put Digital in the unusual position of being the price leader in the market. 
Analysts said Digital's move is likely to blunt the success of workstation makers Sun Microsystems Inc., of Mountain View, Calif., and Apollo Computer Corp., of Chelmsford, Mass. -- at least temporarily. 

   The lower-priced Digital workstations -- powerful personal computers used by engineers for designing products and writing software -- may also compete with higher-priced personal computers made by International Business Machines Corp. and others. 

   "I was flabbergasted. 
This is the announcement of the year," said John Logan, an analyst with Yankee Group in Boston. 
"They have announced the Apollo-killer and laid the groundwork for competing with (IBM's) PS-2" he added. 

   Digital said it will start selling a new monochrome workstation for $4,600 in December. 
It also said it will cut the price on its existing VAXstation 2000 unit with a 19-inch monochrome monitor 48%, to $5,400 from $10,500. 
Currently, the lowest priced workstation is a Sun model with a 19-inch monochrome monitor priced at $4,900. 
In addition, Digital will begin selling in December a color VAXstation 2000 for $7,900, well below the price of any competing products. 
"It's caught everybody off guard. 
You don't expect Digital to be as price competitive as this," said Vicki Brown, a market researcher with International Data Corp., Framingham, Mass. 

   Digital has been highly successful in the past 18 months because all its computers communicate easily and share the same software. 
In the past, its executives have said it didn't need to compete on price because customers were willing to pay for the communications. 
However, with about a 10% share, it has been a weak fourth in the workstation market behind Sun, Apollo and Hewlett Packard Co. of Palo Alto, Calif., according to Dataquest Inc., a San Jose, Calif., market research firm. 

   "We made a decision to break the price barrier. 
We wanted to show we're . . . serious," said Christopher Reed, a marketing manager with Digital. 

   Market leaders Sun and Apollo downplayed the announcement. 
Edward Zander, vice president, marketing, at Apollo noted that Digital didn't announce any new technology. 
"With what we have today and what we have coming in the future, we will be able to maintain a good healthy position," he said. 

   John Hime, director of product marketing at Sun said his company's success "really did wake up the sleeping elephant." 
However, he said that Sun's lowest-priced workstation is faster than Digital's lowest-priced product and predicted Digital's new products will sell mostly to established Digital customers. 

   On Monday, word of the price cuts apparently leaked out and both Apollo and Sun stock prices fell sharply. 
However, they rebounded yesterday. 
In national over-the-counter trading Sun shares closed at $40.875, up $2.375 and Apollo shares rose 62.5 cents to $21.875. 
In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Digital closed at $166.125, up 50 cents a share. 

   Mark Stahlman, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein, said he thinks the newly priced products "will be enormously successful" but predicted that neither Sun nor Apollo will be hurt, because Digital will broaden the market. 
He said both of the smaller companies are expected to introduce new products this summer. 

   Digital said it expects the lower-priced workstations will be popular in non-engineering fields such as desktop publishing, banking, insurance and security trading as well as in the traditional engineering markets. 
All the workstation vendors have been broadening their sales efforts. 
Sun, in particular, has said it sees its workstations as alternatives to personal computers, and yesterday Digital echoed the same theme. 

   In contrast to personal computers, workstations can do many different tasks at once, communicate easily in networks with other workstations and display much sharper text and graphics on larger display screens. 
However, the newest personal computers based on the Intel Corp. 80386 microprocessor and other advanced chips have workstation-like speed and late next year they will gain many of the other workstation capabilities in multitasking and graphics. 

   The personal computer market is much larger than the workstation market. 
Some nine million personal computers have been sold, compared with about 150,000 workstations. 
The workstation market, however, amounted to $1.5 billion last year and is expected to grow almost 50% this year, according to Dataquest, making it one of the fastest growing segments of the computer industry. 

</TEXT>
