<HEAD>Matsushita Says Ally To Use AT&amp;T-Sun Design</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. is lining up on
the side of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Sun Microsystems
Inc. in a high-stakes competition over a critical piece of computer
software.
   Matsushita said Monday that a close U.S. business ally has
concluded a licensing agreement with AT&amp;T and Sun to use their
Sparc computer architecture in a new engineering workstation.
   The Sparc design is tailored for use with AT&amp;T's latest version
of Unix. Unix is a base layer of software that allows programs to
run on a variety of computer models.
   The version of Unix developed by AT&amp;T with Sun has been
challenged by an industry group that says the popular software
should not be controlled by one company. That group includes such
powerhouses as International Business Machines Corp., Digital
Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   Matsushita's decision to jump into the fast-growing workstation
market ends an effective 24-year absence from the field of
high-powered computers. Workstations are fast computers with strong
graphics capabilities that are typically used by scientists and
engineers.
   Matsushita said it plans to build the central processing unit
for the workstations designed by Solbourne Computer Inc. of
Longmont, Colo., and Solbourne would supply the rest of the
workstation's components and sell it under its own brand name in
the United States.
   Matsushita owns 52 percent of Solbourne, according to Mike
Kitadeya, a spokesman for Matsushita's U.S. subsidiary.
   Solbourne hopes to put a workstation on sale in the United
States early next year, Kitadeya said.
   Matsushita's decision to enter the fray over Unix, though
indirectly for the time being, on the side of Sparc could affect
the opinions of other Japanese electronics makers.
</TEXT>
