<SECOND>PM-IBM Workstations, 1st Ld-Writethru,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debuts Line of Workstations Aimed At Fast-Growing Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-8 UPDATE with news conference, quote, picks up 6th
graf pvs, The workstation...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM unveiled a line of computer workstations
today that experts say should help the computer giant win a stake
in an important market it never has mastered.
   ``The opportunity is big _ it's growing at over 30 percent a
year, and it's mostly a new opportunity for IBM,'' President Jack
D. Kuehler told a news conference.
   Kuehler said the new workstations, designed for business users,
``outperform the newest and best that our competitors offer.''
   International Business Machines Corp. aides showed reporters
nine high-performance workstations and computer file-servers, with
prices ranging from $13,000 to more than $74,000.
   Industry analysts say the machines are impressive for their
operating speed and features and should be received favorably by
engineers, their target market.
   Workstations are desktop machines that are much more powerful
than personal computers. Some even match the power of mainframes.
They are used for such processing-intensive tasks as computer
modeling of new products.
   While the workstation market is a small segment of the overall
computer industry, it is among the fastest-growing, and uses for
the machines are expanding.
   IBM introduced a workstation line several years ago, the RT
line, but it captured less than 3 percent of market. Experts
consider the machines underpowered and overpriced.
   The workstation field is dominated by Sun Microsystems Inc.,
Digital Equipment Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.
   The new IBM machines, like the workstations they replace, are
based on a version of the Unix operating system, the underlying
software that directs basic computer functions.
   Unix, developed by American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., is
becoming the computer industry standard, allowing machines from
different manufacturers to be linked together.
   Until now, IBM had not wholeheartedly embraced Unix, preferring
its own proprietary operating systems instead. The fact that the
workstations are Unix-based shows IBM is serious about this market,
analysts say.
   Like the older IBM workstations, the new models also are based
on reduced-instruction-set computing technology, or RISC, which
simplifies the circuitry of a computer's central processor to
increase speed and offer cost savings. The powerful machines are
expected to offer color, 3-D graphics capability.
   Analysts say one factor in the success of the new line, called
the RISC System 6000, will be the availability of applications
software, or the programs that provide the actual uses of a
computer, such as engineering modeling.
   Though the machines are Unix-based, IBM uses its own version of
Unix, called AIX, that is not compatible with Unix applications
programs written for other companies' machines. That means programs
must be rewritten for the IBM workstations.
   IBM has been working with software companies for some time to
develop programs for the new machines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

